---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout title="Mass Surveillance Came to Graham County">
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="tagline">Graham County &middot; Arizona &middot; 2026</p>
    <h1>Mass Surveillance Came to Safford</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">
      Cameras on our roads log every car that passes. Five Arizona towns have already removed or blocked them. We think Safford should be the sixth. Here's what they really do, and how to get them out.
    </p>
    <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
      <a href={`${base}cameras/`} class="btn">What It Really Does</a>
      <a href={`${base}petition/`} class="btn btn-outline">Take Action</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="content">
    <div class="stat-grid">
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-number">45+</div>
        <div class="stat-label">ALPR cameras mapped in Graham County (44 Flock, 1 Motorola)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-number">12,000+</div>
        <div class="stat-label">Searches Scottsdale PD ran on the shared Arizona database</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-number">5</div>
        <div class="stat-label">Arizona communities that already removed or blocked Flock</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <div class="stat-number">30</div>
        <div class="stat-label">Days your plate, location, and vehicle profile are stored</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>The Short Version</h2>
    <p>
      Flock Safety cameras went up around Safford. Local law enforcement calls them an investigative tool that only reads license plates, with safeguards, audits, and nothing to worry about. Watch the interview yourself &mdash; we link it on the <a href={`${base}safford/`}>Local</a> page.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>What we want is simple: the cameras come out.</strong> That isn't a fantasy. Five Arizona communities have already removed or blocked Flock &mdash; Sedona, Flagstaff, South Tucson, Cochise County, and Sierra Vista. Small towns, same state, same network. Safford can be next.
    </p>
    <p>
      Until then, the floor is transparency. We have a legal right to see who has been searching the cameras in our county, and that audit is the evidence that wins the bigger fight. The problem was never whether Graham County officers are good people. The problem is the network: every plate those cameras read feeds a national system thousands of agencies can search, and that system has already been misused across Arizona for exactly the things people were told it wouldn't be.
    </p>

    <h2>Three Things To Know</h2>

    <a href={`${base}cameras/`} class="card">
      <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(230, 57, 70, 0.2); color: #E63946;">Learn &middot; 01</span>
      <h3>It's Not Just a Plate Reader</h3>
      <p>Flock's own product is called "Vehicle Fingerprint." It logs your make, color, dents, roof rack, and bumper stickers, then lets police search for people by description. It connects to doorbell cameras and predictive-policing platforms.</p>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li>Tracks your car even with <strong>no visible plate</strong></li>
        <li>AI search for <strong>"man in a camo hat"</strong>, no face needed</li>
        <li>Partnered with <strong>Ring</strong> doorbells in 2025, until public backlash killed the deal in Feb 2026</li>
      </ul>
    </a>

    <a href={`${base}network/`} class="card">
      <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(244, 162, 97, 0.2); color: #F4A261;">Learn &middot; 02</span>
      <h3>The Network Has Already Been Abused</h3>
      <p>This isn't hypothetical and it isn't far away. On the same network Graham County feeds, agencies across Arizona and the country have run searches that had nothing to do with stolen cars.</p>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li><strong>Sedona, Flagstaff, South Tucson</strong> removed their cameras; <strong>Cochise County</strong> blocked them</li>
        <li>A <strong>Glendale officer</strong> typed an ethnic slur as a search reason</li>
        <li>Arizona agencies ran <strong>No Kings protest</strong> searches, Tempe looked for "any red vehicle"</li>
      </ul>
    </a>

    <a href={`${base}architecture/`} class="card">
      <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(157, 78, 221, 0.2); color: #9D4EDD;">Learn &middot; 03</span>
      <h3>The Camera Is the Front Door</h3>
      <p>Flock's data platform can plug into Palantir, the company that builds ICE's deportation system and the Pentagon's AI targeting system. The same architecture that tracks a stolen car can track a person, a protester, a deportation target.</p>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li>Palantir runs <strong>ImmigrationOS</strong> and the Pentagon's <strong>Maven</strong> targeting system</li>
        <li>Tested on <strong>immigrants and Palestinians</strong> first</li>
        <li>A federal directive now lists <strong>"anti-capitalist" and "anti-fascist"</strong> as extremism markers</li>
      </ul>
    </a>

    <div class="cta-banner">
      <h3>You Can Actually Do Something</h3>
      <p>
        Arizona public records law (A.R.S. &sect; 39-121) gives you the right to see who has been searching the cameras in your community. We wrote the request for you. Copy, paste, send.
      </p>
      <a href={`${base}records/`} class="btn">Get the Records Request</a>
    </div>

    <div class="cta-banner">
      <h3>This Has Already Been Won, Five Times</h3>
      <p>
        Sedona, Flagstaff, South Tucson, Cochise County, and Sierra Vista all canceled or blocked Flock. Same state, same network, same company. See exactly how they did it, and how Safford can be next.
      </p>
      <a href={`${base}wins/`} class="btn">How Other AZ Towns Won</a>
    </div>

    <h2>Who's Behind This</h2>
    <p>
      DeFlock Safford is a project of The Mnemosyne Research Institute, a local research operation in Graham County. We're not anti-police. We're against a private surveillance network with no warrant requirement, sold to our town, that we don't control and can't see into.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every number on this site links to a primary document or major news report. If we got something wrong, we want to know. That's the whole point.
    </p>
    <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem; color: var(--color-muted);">
      &mdash; The Mnemosyne Research Institute<br />
      Safford, Arizona
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>
